fields.subject: {{first_name}} {{last_name}} ({{username}}), Please Verify Your Email Account in {{portal_title}}
fields.body:
Dear {{first_name}} {{last_name}},

Someone has created an account with this email address. If this was you, click the link below to verify your email address:

{{url}}

If you didn't create this account, just ignore this message.

fields.subject: New User Account Was Created Successfully
{{first_name}} {{last_name}} ({{username}}), Reset your password in {{portal_title}}
fields.body:
Dear {{first_name}} {{last_name}},

Please click the link below to reset your password. This link is valid for 24 hours.

{{url}}

If you didn't request to reset your password, just ignore this message.

Future Water Project is ....

To better assess water resources availability in the future, we used the USDA Soil-Water Assessment Tool software package and climate projections from an ensemble of 10 global climate models (GCMs) to simulate climate change impacts on the water cycles in the Wabash River Basin, which covers most of Indiana. Our computer simulations predicted the water cycles to the year 2100 under two IPCC CO2 emission scenarios: RCP 4.5 and 8.5, representing a medium- and high-emissions scenario, respectively.

Successful management of water resources requires us all not only to put the best sciences into our forecasts but also to change the ways that scientific results are communicated. We have endeavored to make the model and modeling results accessible to scholar collaborators and policy makers, and the public.

Future Water Project is ....

To better assess water resources availability in the future, we used the USDA Soil-Water Assessment Tool software package and climate projections from an ensemble of 10 global climate models (GCMs) to simulate climate change impacts on the water cycles in the Wabash River Basin, which covers most of Indiana. Our computer simulations predicted the water cycles to the year 2100 under two IPCC CO2 emission scenarios: RCP 4.5 and 8.5, representing a medium- and high-emissions scenario, respectively.

Successful management of water resources requires us all not only to put the best sciences into our forecasts but also to change the ways that scientific results are communicated. We have endeavored to make the model and modeling results accessible to scholar collaborators and policy makers, and the public.

\"}, \"id\": \"ad86b56c-e36b-47f6-bae2-fb1613952b2d\"}]", "show_navbar": "no", "show_nav_extra": "no", "show_footer": "no", "row": [{"pk": 1, "sort_order": 0, "body": "[{\"type\": \"image_block\", \"value\": {\"image\": 4, \"caption\": \"\", \"width\": \"100%\", \"height\": null, \"redirect_url\": \"\", \"custom_class\": \"col-md-12 banner image loaded\"}, \"id\": \"b93aac1f-c763-4226-8e00-a63d8a8f96e0\"}, {\"type\": \"heading_block\", \"value\": {\"heading_text\": \"Future Water Project is ....\", \"size\": \"h4\", \"custom_class\": \"offset-md-1 col-md-2 mt-5\"}, \"id\": \"d9cf8c62-8c9a-46be-aff7-f8a88881f211\"}, {\"type\": \"heading_block\", \"value\": {\"heading_text\": \"Explore Modeling Results\", \"size\": \"h4\", \"custom_class\": \"col-md-8 ml-auto mt-5\"}, \"id\": \"7fbd325a-2335-4752-a58e-605b7d8d78e8\"}, {\"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"value\": {\"custom_class\": \"col-md-5 mx-auto\", \"body\": \"

To better assess water resources availability in the future, we used the USDA Soil-Water Assessment Tool software package and climate projections from an ensemble of 10 global climate models (GCMs) to simulate climate change impacts on the water cycles in the Wabash River Basin, which covers most of Indiana. Our computer simulations predicted the water cycles to the year 2100 under two IPCC CO2 emission scenarios: RCP 4.5 and 8.5, representing a medium- and high-emissions scenario, respectively.

Successful management of water resources requires us all not only to put the best sciences into our forecasts but also to change the ways that scientific results are communicated. We have endeavored to make the model and modeling results accessible to scholar collaborators and policy makers, and the public.

\"}, \"id\": \"9b370eb9-cd01-4472-9c47-d42da51472ba\"}, {\"type\": \"bootstrap_button\", \"value\": {\"button_text\": \"Future Water Home\", \"button_link\": \"https://futurewater.indiana.edu/\", \"button_color\": \"btn-danger\", \"button_size\": \"\", \"custom_class\": \"\"}, \"id\": \"8f6ffb6f-01db-4e61-b448-05ea76087f90\"}, {\"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"value\": {\"custom_class\": \"col-md-5 mt-5\", \"body\": \"

Some modeling results are shown as interactive plots, maps, and data download. Users can click on a subbasin of interest, choose a CO2 emission scenario, and choose a time period. The maps will show forecasts of precipitation, streamflow level, and soil moisture. Please note that all models carry uncertainties and the hydrological models propagate the uncertainties in the atmospheric circulation model errors. You can access the results with IU CAS login credentials.

  • Easy job submissions to IU computing resources, BigRed2, Karst and Mason.

  • Share your research experimental data with fellow researchers.
  • You can request your application on IU portal for job submissions.

Login Register

To better assess water resources availability in the future, we used the USDA Soil-Water Assessment Tool software package and climate projections from an ensemble of 10 global climate models (GCMs) to simulate climate change impacts on the water cycles in the Wabash River Basin, which covers most of Indiana. Our computer simulations predicted the water cycles to the year 2100 under two IPCC CO2 emission scenarios: RCP 4.5 and 8.5, representing a medium- and high-emissions scenario, respectively.

Successful management of water resources requires us all not only to put the best sciences into our forecasts but also to change the ways that scientific results are communicated. We have endeavored to make the model and modeling results accessible to scholar collaborators and policy makers, and the public.

\"}, \"id\": \"9b370eb9-cd01-4472-9c47-d42da51472ba\"}, {\"type\": \"bootstrap_button\", \"value\": {\"button_text\": \"Future Water Home\", \"button_link\": \"https://futurewater.indiana.edu/\", \"button_color\": \"btn-danger\", \"button_size\": \"\", \"custom_class\": \"\"}, \"id\": \"8f6ffb6f-01db-4e61-b448-05ea76087f90\"}, {\"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"value\": {\"custom_class\": \"col-md-4 mt-5\", \"body\": \"

Some modeling results are shown as interactive plots, maps, and data download. Users can click on a subbasin of interest, choose a CO2 emission scenario, and choose a time period. The maps will show forecasts of precipitation, streamflow level, and soil moisture. Please note that all models carry uncertainties and the hydrological models propagate the uncertainties in the atmospheric circulation model errors. You can access the results with IU CAS login credentials.

Future Water Computations

Computations are done by water resource experts and scholar collaborators. Our hydrological data and model source codes will be hosted on IU\\u2019s exceptional High-Performance Computing cyberinfrastructure. Collaborators can either run their own models by modifying the input files or mine the huge catches of modeling output files stored on Big Red II and analyze the data to answer questions related to their own disciplines. These models could become research infrastructure for student dissertation research across schools and disciplines with downstream applications, for instances of flood frequency forecasting, social-economic modeling, and animal migrations. We envision a near future where our models and gateway, once fully developed, become a platform for future research collaboration and service toward better management of water quantity and water quality in Indiana.

To better assess water resources availability in the future, we used the USDA Soil-Water Assessment Tool software package and climate projections from an ensemble of 10 global climate models (GCMs) to simulate climate change impacts on the water cycles in the Wabash River Basin, which covers most of Indiana. Our computer simulations predicted the water cycles to the year 2100 under two IPCC CO2 emission scenarios: RCP 4.5 and 8.5, representing a medium- and high-emissions scenario, respectively.

Successful management of water resources requires us all not only to put the best sciences into our forecasts but also to change the ways that scientific results are communicated. We have endeavored to make the model and modeling results accessible to scholar collaborators and policy makers, and the public.

\"}, \"id\": \"9b370eb9-cd01-4472-9c47-d42da51472ba\"}, {\"type\": \"bootstrap_button\", \"value\": {\"button_text\": \"Future Water Home\", \"button_link\": \"https://futurewater.indiana.edu/\", \"button_color\": \"\", \"button_size\": \"\", \"custom_class\": \"offset-md- bg-crimson padded iu-button\"}, \"id\": \"8f6ffb6f-01db-4e61-b448-05ea76087f90\"}, {\"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"value\": {\"custom_class\": \"col-md-4 mt-5\", \"body\": \"

Some modeling results are shown as interactive plots, maps, and data download. Users can click on a subbasin of interest, choose a CO2 emission scenario, and choose a time period. The maps will show forecasts of precipitation, streamflow level, and soil moisture. Please note that all models carry uncertainties and the hydrological models propagate the uncertainties in the atmospheric circulation model errors. You can access the results with IU CAS login credentials.

\"}, \"id\": \"9d04f92c-2b97-436b-b15b-f2d5d75bbc48\"}, {\"type\": \"bootstrap_button\", \"value\": {\"button_text\": \"Explore Results\", \"button_link\": \"https://analysis.futurewater.indiana.edu/\", \"button_color\": \"btn-danger\", \"button_size\": \"\", \"custom_class\": \"\"}, \"id\": \"02e833ba-2c8e-47c1-b864-5bb55d2170d4\"}]", "page": 3}, {"pk": 2, "sort_order": 1, "body": "[{\"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"value\": {\"custom_class\": \"bg-crimson padded pad-top pad-bottom iu-button\", \"body\": \"

Future Water Computations

Computations are done by water resource experts and scholar collaborators. Our hydrological data and model source codes will be hosted on IU\\u2019s exceptional High-Performance Computing cyberinfrastructure. Collaborators can either run their own models by modifying the input files or mine the huge catches of modeling output files stored on Big Red II and analyze the data to answer questions related to their own disciplines. These models could become research infrastructure for student dissertation research across schools and disciplines with downstream applications, for instances of flood frequency forecasting, social-economic modeling, and animal migrations. We envision a near future where our models and gateway, once fully developed, become a platform for future research collaboration and service toward better management of water quantity and water quality in Indiana.

\"}, \"id\": \"b984aa02-ab00-488b-b350-24fb866d1a59\"}, {\"type\": \"image_block\", \"value\": {\"image\": 5, \"caption\": \"\", \"width\": \"1500\", \"height\": 1250, \"redirect_url\": \"\", \"custom_class\": \"bg-crimson padded pad-top pad-bottom iu-button\"}, \"id\": \"ea980756-d4d9-4c9d-b889-de34c3852ffe\"}]", "page": 3}, {"pk": 4, "sort_order": 2, "body": "[{\"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"value\": {\"custom_class\": \"bg-none padded pad-top pad-bottom text-dark\", \"body\": \"

\"}, \"id\": \"040d68b0-50c3-4e90-b5f2-bd31a0c5990f\"}]", "page": 3}]}

To better assess water resource availability in the future, we used the USDA Soil-Water Assessment Tool software package and climate projections from an ensemble of ten general circulation models (GCMs) to simulate climate change impacts on the water cycles in the Wabash River Basin, which covers most of Indiana. Our computer simulations predicted the water cycles to the year 2100 under two IPCC CO2 emission scenarios: RCP 4.5 and 8.5, representing a medium- and high-emissions scenario, respectively.

Successful management of water resources requires us all not only to put the best sciences into our forecasts but also to change the ways that scientific results are communicated. We have endeavored to make the model and modeling results accessible to scholar collaborators, water specialists, policy makers, and the public. Making these results widely available is an expression of our view that making good scientific research easily accessible can help people make good decisions. At the same time, we emphasize that as in many scientific inquiries, we expect that as better data and better sub-models are produced, we will be able to produce even better models and make even better predictions.

\"}, \"id\": \"9b370eb9-cd01-4472-9c47-d42da51472ba\"}, {\"type\": \"bootstrap_button\", \"value\": {\"button_text\": \"Future Water Home\", \"button_link\": \"https://futurewater.indiana.edu/\", \"button_color\": \"btn-danger\", \"button_size\": \"\", \"custom_class\": \"offset-md-1 bg-crimson padded iu-button\"}, \"id\": \"8f6ffb6f-01db-4e61-b448-05ea76087f90\"}, {\"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"value\": {\"custom_class\": \"col-md-5 ml-auto mt-5\", \"body\": \"

Some modeling results are shown as interactive plots, maps, and data download. Users can click on a subbasin of interest, choose a CO2 emission scenario, and choose a time period. The maps will show forecasts of precipitation, streamflow level, and soil moisture. Please note that all models carry uncertainties and the hydrological models propagate the uncertainties in the atmospheric circulation model errors. You can access the results with IU CAS login credentials.

\"}, \"id\": \"9d04f92c-2b97-436b-b15b-f2d5d75bbc48\"}, {\"type\": \"bootstrap_button\", \"value\": {\"button_text\": \"Explore Results\", \"button_link\": \"https://analysis.futurewater.indiana.edu/\", \"button_color\": \"btn-danger\", \"button_size\": \"\", \"custom_class\": \"offset-md-1 bg-crimson padded iu-button\"}, \"id\": \"02e833ba-2c8e-47c1-b864-5bb55d2170d4\"}]", "page": 3}, {"pk": 2, "sort_order": 1, "body": "[{\"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"value\": {\"custom_class\": \"bg-crimson padded pad-top pad-bottom iu-button\", \"body\": \"

Future Water Computations

Computations are done by water resource experts and scholar collaborators. Our hydrological data and model source codes will be hosted on IU\\u2019s exceptional High-Performance Computing cyberinfrastructure. Collaborators can either run their own models by modifying the input files or mine the huge catches of modeling output files stored on Big Red II and analyze the data to answer questions related to their own disciplines. These models could become research infrastructure for student dissertation research across schools and disciplines with downstream applications, for instances of flood frequency forecasting, social-economic modeling, and animal migrations. We envision a near future where our models and gateway, once fully developed, become a platform for future research collaboration and service toward better management of water quantity and water quality in Indiana.

\"}, \"id\": \"b984aa02-ab00-488b-b350-24fb866d1a59\"}, {\"type\": \"image_block\", \"value\": {\"image\": 5, \"caption\": \"\", \"width\": \"1200\", \"height\": 850, \"redirect_url\": \"\", \"custom_class\": \"bg-crimson padded pad-top pad-bottom iu-button\"}, \"id\": \"ea980756-d4d9-4c9d-b889-de34c3852ffe\"}]", "page": 3}, {"pk": 4, "sort_order": 2, "body": "[{\"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"value\": {\"custom_class\": \"grid-item offset-md-3\", \"body\": \"

Gateway PI: Chen Zhu

Email: Chen

The Future Water Science Gateway is hosted at SciGaP gateway platform managed by Science Gateways Research Center

Email: SGRC

\"}, \"id\": \"040d68b0-50c3-4e90-b5f2-bd31a0c5990f\"}]", "page": 3}]}
